<H3> <TI>   Police Seize 60 Grams of Plutonium in Baden-Wuerttemberg </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Seize 60 Grams of Plutonium in Baden-Wuerttemberg </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605193394 Hamburg DPA in German 1750 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2605193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Stuttgart/Karlsruhe (DPA) -- Already at the 
beginning of May, what are probably 60 grams of plutonium 239 
were seized by police during the search of an apartment in 
Baden-Wuerttemberg. For several weeks the authorities in 
southwest Germany obviously did not have any idea of how 
dangerous this find was. Only on Thursday [27 May] did 
investigations by the Land Office for Environmental Protection 
in Karlsruhe show that the material, which is in a small 
cylindrical container, is probably this kind of plutonium, the 
Environment Ministry in Stuttgart announced. 
  According to the Ministry, the amount seized is "highly 
dangerous" and is the so-far largest amount found in 
Baden-Wuerttemberg. However, the amount is not sufficient for 
producing a a nuclear bomb. The material probably comes from an 
Eastern European country. The Stuttgart land Office of Criminal 
Investigations has taken over investigations. 
  Information about the occasion, the place, and the exact 
date 
of the search was not given for "tactical reasons." In 
addition, the Ministry announced that "following initial 
suspicion, the local fire brigade did not register any 
radioactive radiation outside the container." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

