<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "10 Tons of T-4 Explosive Missing, </F>
Mafia Links Sought"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Chieti, May 19 -- About 10 tons of T-4 
explosive, the same used in three car bombings attributed to 
Cosa Nostra, have disappeared from the deposit of an explosives 
manufacturer in Casalbordino, near this central Italian town, 
police announced Thursday [19 May]. 
  Two former executives of the plant have been arrested on 
charges of unlawful possession of explosives, police added. 
  The T-4 explosives, used to make mines, were deposited at 
the 
plant by the Brescia-based manufacturer, Valsella, in 1985. 
  The National Anti-Mafia Directorate is investigating to 
determine possible connections with the three car bombings, 
which include the May 1992 assassination of judge Giovanni 
Falcone, his wife and three bodyguards in Palermo, Sicily. The 
same explosive was used in the May 14 and July 27 1993 bombings 
in Rome and Milan, respectively. Ten people were injured in the 
Rome explosion, five were killed and 12 injured in Milan. 

</TEXT>

