<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Groups Opposing Peace Agreement Burn 10 Buses in Medellin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Groups Opposing Peace Agreement Burn 10 Buses in Medellin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2605144994 Santa fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2605144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpts] Early this morning terrorist groups opposed to 
the peace agreement scheduled to be officially signed today at 
approximately 1100 in the Granizal section of Medellin set fire 
to approximately 10 buses, causing damages amounting to 115 
million pesos. The peace agreement is between the government 
and 600 militia members of Medellin's northeastern and 
northwestern communities. [passage omitted] 
  With the support of the Army and the police, urban bus 
services are gradually being restored to Medellin and the 
surrounding communities. Currently the Granizal area is 
cordoned off and heavily militarized. After 1000 this morning 
in Granizales, during an event led by Government Minister Fabio 
Villegas Ramirez, the peace agreement will be signed by three of 
Medellin's five popular militias. This translates into the 
demobilization and disarmament of approximately 650 men from the 
three armed groups. 
  [Paris AFP in Spanish at 1318 GMT on 26 May reports that 
three taxis, as well as 10 buses, were burned and that no 
injuries or fatalities were reported. The report says that bus 
service in Medellin has been drastically reduced because of fear 
among bus drivers and owners that their vehicles might be 
targeted, adding that authorities believe that the escalation of 
guerrilla activities is related to the 29 May elections.] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

